At any rate the application of the name to Cicero, without strict limitation and definition, may easily lead, as it has led, to serious misconceptions regarding his position. Many of the writers who dub Cicero ‘eclectio’ appear to think that they thereby cast on him a grave reproach. The note or mark ol eclecticism present to the minds of these writers is wantos originality. Now to charge Cicero with wantos originality betrays a failure to catch the spirit os the age in which he lived It was an age os exposition and com- mentation, not an age ol original thought, and this is just as true os the Greek world at that period as of the Roman. No substantially novel views of philosophy had been propounded since the time of Carneades, indeed we might say since the timeor Arcesilas. lt was tacitly assumed ⁸ on all hands that any one who pursued philosophy must needs attach himself to one of the existing schools There was absolutely no demand whatever tor views of truth which professed to be new¹. Originality in a philosopher, sar from being looked upon as a merit, would rather have been treated as asin. Changes indeed, most pro· found and momentous, were in progress. Old dogmas and formulas were continually on the lips of the philosophers, and old controversial battles were incessantly fought over again, yet the spirit os the corn· batants was, vastly different from that of their intellectual foresathers. The change however did not proceed from the speculations ol any in· · dividuals, but was part ol a general movement in culture and society.
